<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>B&amp;ES response to the Energy &amp; Climate Change Select Committee inquiry into heat</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><a name="_Toc365538595"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by B&amp;Es (HOT24)</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:'Verdana Bold'; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Building &amp; Engineering Services Association is the UK's leading trade association for building services engineering contractors, representing the interests of over 1</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">370 firms active in the design, installation, commissioning and maintenance of heating, ventilating, air conditioning, refrigeration and electrical products and equipment.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">B&amp;ES is taking a lead role in the development of sustainable building services engineering</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Recent research we have undertaken amongst our members shows that</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#f3b777; font-family:Symbol; font-size:16pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 133pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-58.8pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">70</span><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">%</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> of them installed renewable technologies in the six months to June 2012</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li><li style="color:#f3b777; font-family:Symbol; font-size:16pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86.56pt; orphans:0; padding-left:12.44pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">59%</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> installed air source heat pumps</span></li><li style="color:#f3b777; font-family:Symbol; font-size:16pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86.56pt; orphans:0; padding-left:12.44pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">43%</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> air</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">-</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">air heat pumps</span></li><li style="color:#f3b777; font-family:Symbol; font-size:16pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 86.56pt; orphans:0; padding-left:12.44pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">40%</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> installed solar thermal</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> and</span></li><li style="color:#f3b777; font-family:Symbol; font-size:16pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 86.66pt; orphans:0; padding-left:12.29pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">38</span><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">%</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> installed biomass boilers</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul></ul></ul></ul></ul><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We are concerned that system performance should be viewed as a whole rather than concentrating on the primary fuel emissions</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Whatever analysis structure is implemented it should always centre on minimising the energy use at point of delivery and also the energy consumed in the systems that then deliver the energy.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">As buildings become more energy efficient through the application of insulation and control of air infiltration, the energy used in the delivery systems can be as much as 40% of the total energy delivered</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This auxiliary energy is invariably electricity with its high CO</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> content.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Against this background, we welcome the Energy and Climate Change </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">elect </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ommittee’s inquiry into Heat and are pleased to submit our response for consideration</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  We have focussed on space and water heating as the areas most covered by our members, and also which make-up the vast bulk of heat demand.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In compiling this submission, we have consulted with our members by circulating an early draft version which was discussed through an online webinar.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Our submission paper presented last year to the Chartered Institute of Building Services Engineers’ Technical Symposium, resulted from research undertaken for the B&amp;ES </span><a href="http://www.b-es.org/files/8013/7710/4985/Integrator_Guide.pdf"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Renewable Systems Integration Guide</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The standards referenced </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">therein make for a quantifiable, audible calculation process applicable to both renewable and traditional energy sources</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We appreciate this paper is too lengthy to provide to committee members with this submission</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> we </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">feel it is very relevant and would much appreciate the opportunity to give oral evidence to the committee and to discuss it with them then</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:30pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:'Verdana Bold'; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538596"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Inquiry questions</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">With regard to the specific questions asked, our responses are as follows:</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538597"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Is the </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Government</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> taking the right approach to reduce heat energy demand</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt">?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Just as people in business or in their homes do not wake up and ask themselves, “</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">how much en</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ergy can we  save today</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">?”, so they do not value heat until they do not have it</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Their main awareness comes when a large utility bill arrives on the doorstep</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">As the production of heat for space heating is seldom of strategic financial importance to people, it attracts little attention except in those areas where there is a major impact</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> eg in buildings such as hospitals and universities</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There are few significant drivers for change and almost always competing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> investment opportunities.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, responsibility for energy demand falls between </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">three dep</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">artments</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Department for Energy and Climate Change</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">(“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DECC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”) </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">where the Energy Efficiency Deployment Office</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EEDO</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> is at the centre of a new drive by </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> to improve the way we use energy across the UK)</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Department for Communities and Local Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CLG</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> - responsible for energy standards in buildings)</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">while the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DEFRA</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">) has an interest in energy with regard to emissions of CO</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Then, at an operational level, there are </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">two </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">main non-departmental </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">al bodies</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the Energy Saving Trust</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, working mainly in the domestic sector</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> and</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; orphans:0; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the Carbon Trust</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, working with industry and innovative energy technologies.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Finally there is </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ofgem</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, the energy regulator and responsible for overseeing the introduction of the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Renewable Heat Incentive</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RHI</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There is no clear lead body with overall responsibility for reducing heat energy demand</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">With no specific market driver and a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> focus, it is difficult to know how much progress is being achieved, with no clear way of being able to calculate overall costs against carbon emissions and wider sustainability issues</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government policy is delivered through an over-complex mix of disparate initiatives: building regulations, planning requirements, the code for sustainable homes, renewable heat incentive, the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Carbon Reduction Commitment Energy Efficiency Scheme</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RCEES</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">) and Green Deal to name but some</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This had led to a ‘tick box’ culture that puts in place minimum requirements at the planning stage, though in effect these requirements are rarely inspected or checked to see if they function </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">as designed.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Overall there is no clear joined up approach; more emphasis needs to be made on improving the heat efficiency of commercial and housing projects, which could be incentivised via the planning system, section 106 agreements and proper enforcement</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">What is needed is a results-based process</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> rather than a theoretical planning design process</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538598"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What progress is the </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Government</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> making on reducing the demand for heat?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Reduction in demand for heat should not be confused with de-carbonisation.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> has put in place several initiatives that aim to reduce demand for heat, most significantly the Green Deal / ECO and the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">RHI </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">(designed to encourage a switch to renewable technologies, the heat saving element comes from a requirement to carry out the minimum insulation improvements specified in the Green Deal assessment to trigger funding)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The Government has also published revisions to Part L of the Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">So in principle, some progress is being made</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">However, so far the Green Deal has proven disappointing with little take-up by consumers mainly due to a lack of detailed communication and explanation (the budget for digital switchover was </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> £146</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> million</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, by comparison the budget for Green Deal is £2.9</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> million</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">), as well as perceived high interest rates and concerns over the impact upon resale values of properties that have had Green Deal funded improvements.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The changes to Part L are broadly welcomed though there is a lack of ambition in the new regulations, particularly in relation to the absence of new standards for refurbishments and existing homes, which are responsible for the majority of the UK’s emissions</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Due to the prevailing economic conditions, many developments which have been granted planning permission under the old regulations have stalled, hence we are likely see a continuation to design to the old standards for some time, as developers have </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">three</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> years to start a development from being given planning permission</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Overall, we observe that the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">overnment is gaining a reputation for setting headline grabbing green targets, then watering down targets when it comes to putting in place the details that lead to firm action and progress in reducing demand for heat</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This is particularly true in respect of housebuilding</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> where lobbying has been very effective in gaining a softening of targets</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  There is a disconnect, between what is designed and approved for planning and what is built and implemented.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There is a particular problem in the new build housing sector with the increasing number of tower blocks that are being built</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Builders are encouraged to install centralised heating plant and onsite generation through planning and the code for sustainable homes (which triggers funding for social housing)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">These systems are complex and require close control, usually through a combination of individual controls in </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">the flats and a central </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Building Management System</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">BMS</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The problem with such buildings is that there is usually no clear ‘owner’ of the building’s BMS, so that typically, individual flat dwellers have no right to information from the developer or freeholder</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">David Frise, B&amp;ES’s </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ead of </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">ustainability, has personal experience of this situation </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> even though he is a director of his apartment block’s residents association, he has been refused meaningful information from the developer and the freeholder has no interest in getting involved</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The result is that the system does not operate correctly but the residents cannot get the necessary information to make it work</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This is an example of the planner’s carbon and energy reduction intent being met through the installation of equipment but with no regard being paid to the “</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">does it work</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">” element</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538599"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Biomass is deemed a key fuel for heat production from both the cost and GHG perspectives</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What should be done to ensure methods of calculating biomass GHG balance represent an accurate picture?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There should be ‘whole cycle’ analysis and consideration of the transport carbon costs and the displacement of food production, together with consideration of the true embodied energy of any processing of fuels, such as compressed wood pellets or liquefaction of crops.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538600"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There are sustainability guidelines for biomass</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">o these go far enough?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">No</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The guidelines that are in place need to be more focussed and integrated</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The Bio-liquid and the Solid and Gaseous Biomass Carbon Calculators are not user friendly</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Biomass technology is not always as ‘green’ as it is perceived</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Certain fuel sources </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> in particular roundwood specifically grown for biomass installations </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> may not deliver the carbon paybacks needed to meet national emissions targets</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It is also important that the correct method of measuring environmental performance be used</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">A B&amp;ES Forum has advised the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> to consider the ‘Green Ticks’ scheme operated by the Green Business Network</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This gives organisations credit for putting suitable policies in place; complying with legislation, reviewing suppliers, enthusing staff and using robust environmental management</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Green Ticks would be a way of ensuring all ‘rival’ methodologies used to assess the performance of buildings receive credit and are operated in a complementary way.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The new requirements for the RHI for sustainable biomass fuel supply and air quality controls that were recently introduced are welcomed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538601"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What will the local environmental impact (for example</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> air pollution) be from the use of heat generation in urban areas, for example CHP units?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">One specific observation we would like to make is for </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> to reconsider providing support for biomass systems in urban settings, due to air quality issues</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We should like to commend to the committee the </span><a href="http://www.policyexchange.org.uk/publications/category/item/something-in-the-air-the-forgotten-crisis-of-britain-s-poor-air-quality"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Policy Exchange Report</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Something in the Air - The forgotten crisis of Britain’s poor air quality</span></a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, which says the RHI should </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">not support biomass technologies in cities</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What are the relative merits of using gas to directly provide space heating</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, c</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ompared to centralised electricity production plus domestic heat pumps? </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Gas is a reliable, fully-proven fuel source</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Until such time as electricity generation is significantly de</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">carbonised, mains gas is the best option where it is available.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Ofgem has been warning about looming electricity shortages and this in turn is focusing more attention on energy security</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">’s electricity generation strategy is based around a switch from fossil fuels to a de-carbonised grid through nuclear, wind, biomass and some localised generation, eg solar PV</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">While welcome in principle, delays to this programme mean we are somewhere between the two, with the grid de</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">carbonisation plan years behind schedule</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In any case, planning requirements and funding are driving inappropriate choices</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">B&amp;ES is seeing heat pump and biomass installations that will not achieve any net carbon emissions savings, where gas with energy efficiency upgrades would be less costly, more effective and easier to achieve</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This is particularly prevalent on social housing projects</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538602"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Why is community heating/CHP not more common in the UK?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This is largely due to inadequate and ineffective planning legislation and the complexity of building ownership, ie</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">freehold / leasehold / tenant agreements</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There is a fear that such systems will not work and will in turn impact back on the landlord, building owner or occupier</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The key is to ensure CHP is properly specified and designed</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Most of the problems users have had with CHP in the past were related to over-sizing, which meant the CHP did not run continuously</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Ideally, it should be sized to about 15% of the heat demand, this will mean the engine keeps working hard and continually generating ‘free’ electricity while satisfying the increasing need for low cost, low carbon heat.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">CHP now provides 7.5% of the UK’s electricity requirements and saves 14 million tonnes of CO</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">2</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> per year, according to </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">DECC</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">However, mis-selling and false promises have been a problem</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">CHP has suffered in the past from being misapplied including being used simply to get a tick in a box from a planning officer so as to gain planning permission for a development</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Another often missed opportunity has been the failure to ‘marry’ several technologies to further reduce carbon intensity</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">For example, electricity generated by on-site CHP can be used to power electric heat pumps </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> so increasing the already significant energy and carbon emission benefits of each technology.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">The Carbon Trust has carried out extensive field trials in the UK and concluded that “</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">a mini-CHP unit can provide savings of between 15% and 20% when it is applied as the lead boiler</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It works best in applications with high and continuous heating loads like hospitals, leisure centres, sheltered accommodation and fire stations, because the longer it is running to meet heating demand, the more efficient it </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538603"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What are the lock-in, costs and GHG savings from the promotion of different forms of domestic heating solution?</span></a><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This is such a wide and generalised question that we feel unable to provide a reasoned response.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538604"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Should the </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">G</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">overnment take further any specific actions in relation to cooling?</span></a><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Heat used for cooling through absorption chillers is included in the RHI because it counts under the Renewable Energy Directive (</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">RED</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Cooling generated by heat pumps is not included</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">With ground source heat pumps in particular, cooling is one half of the equation</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, eg </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">cooling in summer replenishes the heat store for the winter, so improving the overall efficiency of the system</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Efforts should therefore be made to have this included within the RED</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538605"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Why does the RHI not seem to promote heat pumps successfully?</span></a><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">For single technology suppliers, Biomass is a far easier sell</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Seemingly an easier technology to design and install, it can often be added to a conventional heating system without alteration, as it operates at the same temperatures as say an oil fired system</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It therefore works well for the off-gas grid boiler replacement market</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Heat pumps need to operate at lower temperatures to achieve the higher COPs (“co-efficient of performances”) that give lower running costs</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">In new-build this is not a problem because the heating system can be designed for lower temperatures with </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">under floor</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> heating or larger radiators</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Replacement boilers however would require system upgrades - eg, upsizing of radiators - that add to the costs and inconvenience to the householder</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There can also be problems in rural areas with inadequate electrical supplies unable to support the additional electrical loads required by heat pumps</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538606"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How successful will the RHI be when rolled out to households?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">This would need a definition of success not currently made clear by </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Industry has broadly welcomed the scheme and it has led to a marked increase in interest from householders as reported by B&amp;ES installer members</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">A number of issues have been raised around contradictory advice from a Green Deal Assessment (“GDA”) and the Microgeneration Installer Standards (“MIS”)</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We have seen several cases of a GDA recommending one technology, Liquefied Petroleum Gas, whilst the MIS calculation suggested Air Source Heat Pump was the better solution</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Clearly these anomalies need to be ironed out</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">If not, while there will be many more installations, some may not be appropriate There is no benefit from installing renewable technologies (except solar thermal) where the gas grid is available</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="color:#ec881d; display:inline; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none; text-transform:none; vertical-align:baseline">2.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Toc365538607"><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Thermal storage is a potential useful method of balancing electricity/energy demand</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> both diurnally and annually</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">is </span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Government</span><span style="color:#b6650f; font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> policy doing to promote thermal storage, and should it do more/different?</span></a></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We are not clear on how much support the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> is giving to thermal storage</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">It barely warranted a mention in the </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">’s December 2011</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Carbon Plan: Delivering our </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">l</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ow </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">c</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">arbon </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">f</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">uture</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There is potential for more encouragement of onsite thermal storage in locations that have the space for it such as schools, office blocks and hospitals</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  Thermal storage can be successful if combined with smart tariffs and metering, which encourage individuals and organisations to plan when they use, generate and store heat.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">Last year, in conjunction with the Technology Strategy Board, DECC launched an Advanced Heat Storage Competition for small businesses, a small-scale</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">but welcome initiative</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">We would like to see more of this type of programme with greater involvement of trade associations like ourselves.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/48478/5412-decc-advanced-heat-storage-project-brief.pdf"><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:none">DECC Advance Heat Storage Project Brief</span></a><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:6pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">There is similar potential in the household sector with regard to the increasing number of tower blocks that are being built in British cities by construction companies to address the need for affordable housing</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">However, an issue with such buildings is that there is usually no clear ‘owner’ of the building’s Building Management System, so that typically, individual flat dwellers have no right to information from the management company or freeholder</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; text-transform:none">September</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; text-transform:uppercase"> 2013</span></p></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:always" /><div><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; page-break-before:always; text-align:right; widows:0"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Verdana; font-size:8pt; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:48pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#260859; font-family:Verdana; font-size:7pt; font-style:italic">Copyright © 2013 by the</span><br /><span style="color:#260859; font-family:Verdana; font-size:7pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Building &amp; Engineering Services Association</span></p><p style="line-height:9pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#260859; font-family:Verdana; font-size:7pt; font-style:italic">All rights reserved</span><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," width="679" height="17" alt="Generic Keyline 180mm" style="float:left; margin:0pt 9pt" /></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="color:#ec881d; font-family:Verdana; font-size:6pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">B&amp;ES State of Trade Survey</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt"> - 6-month period to June 2013, published August 2013</span></p></body></html>